The paper deals with optimization problems related to graphs and networks, which are typical topics in computer science. The use of dynamic programming and greedy algorithms suggests that the paper belongs to the category of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The applications mentioned in the abstract (item-placement problem, Ads-placement problem, resource-placement problem) are related to social networks, advertisement networks, and P2P networks, which are typical topics in social and information networks (cs.SI) and social computing (cs.SOC). The use of submodular set function maximization and random walks suggests that the paper may also belong to the category of machine learning (cs.LG) and information theory (cs.IT).
